'''Anna Muylaert''' (born April 21, 1964) is a Brazilian screenwriter and [[television director|television]] and [[film director]].

==Education and Early Career==
Anna studied filmmaking at the School of Communications and Arts at [[University of São Paulo]] (USP) from 1980 to 1984.<ref name=istoe>{{cite web | url=http://www.terra.com.br/istoegente/161/reportagens/anna_muylaert.htm | title=Uma voz inteligente | date=September 2, 2002 | author=Alves Jr., Dirceu | work=[[IstoÉ|IstoÉ Gente]] | publisher=Editora Três | accessdate=April 26, 2014 | language=Portuguese}}</ref> She became a [[film critic]] for ''[[IstoÉ]]'' and ''[[O Estado de S. Paulo]]'' and in 1988 she joined the staff of [[Rede Gazeta]]'s program ''TV Mix''.<ref name=istoe/><ref name=2uol>{{cite web | url=http://www2.uol.com.br/durvaldiscos/criticas/critica6.htm | title=Anna Muylaert, premiada em Gramado, fala de seu longa de estréia Durval Discos | publisher=[[Universo Online]] | accessdate=April 26, 2014 | language=Portuguese}}</ref> In 1999, she worked as an editor and reporter on [[TV Cultura]]'s ''Matéria-Prima''. She also wrote scripts for the Cultura programs ''Mundo da Lua'' (1991–92) and ''[[Castelo Rá-Tim-Bum]]'' (1994–97).<ref name=istoe/>

==Directing career==
Muylaert has directed six short films—the most notable being ''A Origem dos Bebês Segundo Kiki Cavalcanti'' (1995) which won awards at Rio Cine e Cine Ceará<ref name=2uol/><ref name=revista>{{cite web | url=http://revistadecinema.uol.com.br/index.php/2012/10/a-trajetoria-critica-de-anna-muylaert/ | title=A trajetória crítica de Anna Muylaert | author=August, Heitor | date=October 3, 2012 | work=Revista de Cinema | accessdate=April 26, 2014 | language=Portuguese}}</ref>—before directing her first feature film, ''[[Durval Discos]]'' (2002).<ref name=istoe/> It won seven awards out of fourteen nominations at [[Festival de Gramado]], including Best Director and Best Film.<ref name=istoe/> Seven years later, she released her second film, ''[[É Proibido Fumar (film)|É Proibido Fumar]]'', which won eight awards at [[Festival de Brasília]], including Best Screenplay and Best Film.<ref name=revista/> Muylaert directed ''[[Chamada a Cobrar]]'' (2012), based on a [[television film]] ''Para Aceitá-la Continue na Linha'' (2010), which she also directed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/ilustrada/1174577-novo-filme-de-anna-muylaert-une-crime-e-descoberta-pessoal.shtml | title=Novo filme de Anna Muylaert une crime e descoberta pessoal | author=Pontes, Trajano | date=October 25, 2012 | work=[[Folha de S.Paulo]] | publisher=Grupo Folha | accessdate=April 26, 2014 | language=Portuguese}}</ref> Her fourth film, ''[[The Second Mother (2015 film)|The Second Mother]]'', entered the 2015 [[Sundance Film Festival]] and Panorama at Berlinale film festival, where the film received the Audience Award.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sundance.org/blogs/news/us-world-and-next-films-announced-for-2015-festival | title=Sundance Institute Announces Films in US and World Competitions, for 2015 Sundance Film Festival | date=December 3, 2014 | publisher=sundance.org | accessdate=December 4, 2014}}</ref>

Mulaert's 2016 film ''Don't Call Me Son'' premiered at the [[66th Berlin International Film Festival]].

